  "prompt": "In pregnancy, why is tetracycline contraindicated?",
  "response": "Tetracycline is contraindicated during pregnancy primarily due to its potential to cause harm to the developing fetus. Here are the key reasons:\n\n1. **Tooth Discoloration and Enamel Hypoplasia**: Tetracycline can be deposited in the developing teeth of the fetus, leading to permanent yellow-gray-brown discoloration and enamel hypoplasia. This can affect both the deciduous (baby) teeth and the permanent teeth if taken during the later stages of pregnancy.\n\n2. **Inhibition of Bone Growth**: Tetracycline can also be incorporated into the bones of the developing fetus, potentially leading to growth inhibition and affecting skeletal development.\n\n3. **Potential Liver Toxicity**: There is a risk of hepatotoxicity (liver damage) in the mother, which can have indirect effects on the fetus.\n\n4. **Effect on Microbiome**: Tetracycline can alter the maternal and fetal microbiome, potentially leading to other health issues.\n\nDue to these risks, safer alternative antibiotics are typically recommended during pregnancy. It's important for pregnant women to consult their healthcare provider for any medication decisions.",
